      "hint": "Look for documents like BS 7671, the On-Site Guide, or Guidance Notes, which provide technical 'best practice' rather than legal mandates."
    }
  ]
}

{
  "guidedPractice": {
    "title": "Guided Practice",
    "objective": "Categorize the Health and Safety at Work Act (HASAWA) and BS 7671 into statutory or non-statutory categories.",
    "retrievalTextLines": [
      "Recall the rule from the worked example: 'Acts' and 'Regulations' are passed by Parliament and are Statutory (the law).",
      "Documents like 'Standards', 'Guides', and 'Notes' provide technical instruction and are Non-statutory (best practice).",
      "Consider the Health and Safety at Work Act (HASAWA) and BS 7671 (Requirements for Electrical Installations)."
    ],
    "questionText": "Based on the naming conventions and their legal status, classify both the Health and Safety at Work Act (HASAWA) and BS 7671 as either 'Statutory' or 'Non-statutory'.",
    "answerGuidance": [
      "HASAWA is Statutory",
      "BS 7671 is Non-statutory"
    ],
    "hint": "Look for the word 'Act' in HASAWA to identify it as law. Remember that BS 7671 is the national standard, not a law itself."
  },
  "practice": {
    "title": "Practice",
    "objective": "Independently identify the regulatory status of PUWER, COSHH, and Guidance Notes.",
    "retrievalTextLines": [
      "In the industry, you will deal with various acronyms daily. You must know which ones carry the weight of criminal law.",
      "Statutory regulations are mandatory laws. Non-statutory documents are guidance used to support those laws.",
      "Apply this logic to: PUWER (Provision and Use of Work Equipment Regulations), COSHH (Control of Substances Hazardous to Health), and Guidance Notes."
    ],
    "questionText": "Classify the following three items as either Statutory or Non-statutory: PUWER, COSHH, and Guidance Notes.",
    "answerGuidance": [
      "PUWER: Statutory",
      "COSHH: Statutory",
      "Guidance Notes: Non-statutory"
    ],
    "hint": "If the title ends in 'Regulations', it is a statutory requirement. If it is a 'Note' or 'Guide', it is non-statutory guidance."
  }
}

