    "objective": "Evaluate the relationship between a statutory law (EAWR) and non-statutory guidance (On-Site Guide) in a real-world installation context.",
    "retrievalTextLines": [
      "Statutory regulations like the EAWR are the law of the land and are mandatory.",
      "Non-statutory documents like the On-Site Guide provide the technical 'how-to' for the industry.",
      "While they have different legal weights, they are used together to ensure a safe and compliant installation."
    ],
    "questionText": "You are starting a new installation and refer to both the Electricity at Work Regulations (EAWR) and the On-Site Guide. Contrast these two documents by identifying which is statutory and which is non-statutory, and explain the primary difference in how they legally apply to your work.",
    "answerGuidance": [
      "EAWR is a Statutory Regulation (Law).",
      "The On-Site Guide is Non-statutory Guidance.",
      "The EAWR is a mandatory legal requirement that must be followed to avoid criminal prosecution, whereas the On-Site Guide provides technical instructions and best practice to help an electrician meet those legal standards."
    ],
    "hint": "Think about which document is a 'Regulation' passed by Parliament and which is a 'Guide' for technical standards. One is the law itself; the other is the instruction manual for the law."
  }
}

